AGI -&nbsp; His gesture entered history, immortalized by countless angles, filmed in video, studied frame by frame, moment by moment. Clint Hill, the secret service officer > who jumped on John Fitzgerald Kennedy's limo >while was under fire in Dallas>, died at 93, tormented for decades by the guilt for not being able to prevent the President's assassination. >
<br On November 22, 1963, Hill, who died in his home in California last Friday, had been assigned to the protection of First Lady, Jacqueline Kennedy. He was aboard a car behind Kennedy's limo when he echoed the first shot. He immediately rushed to the presidential couple and encamped on the limo's luggage compartment > while shooting continued. Hill's gesture was immortalized in the now famous Zapruder film, an amateur video > that provided one of the best testimonies of the shooting >.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Hill, originally from the North Dakota, former military officer of the Army, entered the secret service in 1958. He was awarded a prize for his actions in Dallas > and eventually became deputy director. However, the trauma he lived during the assassination led him to retire early from the agency in 1975, at just 43 years old: he was convinced that he could save Kennedy's life and shortly after his retirement he told CBS 60 Minutes to feel responsible.
&nbsp;
"If I had reacted about five tenths of a second faster, maybe a second faster, I wouldn't be here today," he said, "I feel so guilty," If I turned to another direction, I would have done it. It's my fault."
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br With the passing of the years, he returned to Dallas, finally came to the conclusion that he could not save Kennedy's life.> Hill met the journalist Lisa McCubbin in 2009 and collaborated with a successful autobiography, 'Mrs Kennedy and Me'.&nbsp;It was the first of a series of books and Hill and McCubbin ended up falling in love and getting married in 2021.&nbsp;>
