AGI - After the clear victory at the urns, the future also begins to be. The Cdu and the Bavarian sister Csu clearly won the political elections in Germany - with 28.6% and a gain of 4.3 points compared to the vote of 2021 - and the party leader, Friedrich Merz, during the press conference this morning at the Konrad Adenauer Haus, announced to point to Grosse Koalition with the Spd.
&nbsp;
"Together with the Social-Democrats we are in the position to form a government and that is exactly what we want," said the future Chancellor, anticipating that the talks "will begin in the coming days", because the will is to "start rapid and constructive discussions with the Social-Democrats to form a coalition government by Easter".
<div </div
On the urgency of a new government, the president of the industrial group Bdi, Peter Leibinger, said on Sunday the urgent need for the German economy of an executive "who can act very quickly". In the party's seat, in front of journalists, Merz immediately analyzed and commented the incredible growth of AfD - an extreme right-wing party arrived second with 20.8 percent, sending a message to all traditional German political forces.
&nbsp;
"The impennata of the extreme right - which obtained double of the votes compared to the last elections - is the last warned for the traditional German centrist parties" has marked Merz. "For this reason - it has emphasized - I am determined to welcome these signals and to immediately start constructive and fast talks with the Spd". The future chancellor then focused on the role of Europe and the relations with the U.S., which he had already touched with the first speech on Sunday evening after the news of his victory.
&nbsp;
"It is essential to have a united Europe, which speaks with a single voice and has its own defence," Merz said, adding that "it will do everything" to convince the United States that Europe is in their interests. And it is precisely on the last words of Washington - both on Europe and on the war in Ukraine - that the future Chancellor pronounces the strongest phrases. "I'm very concerned about what I've heard in recent months and all the signs that come from the United States indicate that the interest in and for Europe is weakening consistently."
&nbsp;
While not believing that these will be Trump's last words, Merz warns that "it is necessary to prepare for the worst scenario."
&nbsp;
Several are the leaders who congratulated him after the victory, including Israel's premier, Benjamin Netanyahu. On the latter, during the press conference, the leader of the Cdu said that "it is absurd that the Israeli prime minister cannot visit Germany - because of the arrest warrant set out by the International Criminal Court - stressing that with him "will be free to visit the country".
&nbsp;
Despite the possible alliance of government announced by Merz, the main defeat of this electoral round is undoubtedly Olaf Scholz. With 16.4% and 3.8 million votes less, the SPD led by him reached the lowest point ever, and the outgoing Chancellor assumed all responsibility.
&nbsp;
"We tried to do a good job in front of one of the biggest challenges our country has faced since 1945," he said, "as I was responsible for success, I am obviously responsible for the current result."
&nbsp;
Although the defeat of the Social-Democrats is under the eyes of all the co-leader of the Lars Klingbeil party, during the press conference he said that "Germany needs the SPD to be able to act quickly and make decisions".
&nbsp;
The alliance between the two formations - which on paper have solid numbers to govern together without having to resort to a third majority member - would be the fourth "great coalition" in the last two decades, with the Social-Democrats always on the second floor than the Cdu/Csu.
&nbsp;
In total, they can count on 328 of the 630 MPs at the Bundestag. But negotiation will be far from easy and the electoral campaign, strongly polarized, has highlighted significant programmatic differences between the SPD and the conservatives. For Cornelia Woll, professor at the Hertie School in Berlin "the conditions of departure are very difficult", underlining how Merz will have to enter a process of merchanting party policies to develop a platform for a future government alliance.
&nbsp;
In the meantime, the other winner of these elections, the far-right party of AfD - arrived second with 20.8% - immediately after the closing of the ballots, announced he was ready to rule with the Cdu, although Merz immediately excluded this possibility. Weidel, during the press conference held in the morning, revealed that he received personal congratulations from Elon Musk, underlining that the party is now "an internationally recognized power, in contact with everyone, including the Trump administration".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
